review_blob: Cask at Kings Arms on Roupell Street. Russet colour, refreshing and balanced taste gives way to punishing bitterness. Altogether more memorable than in bottle.

Bottle at the Rake with the Stone guys. This is the first really convincing double IPA Ive tried. The hop strength goes without saying but rather than stripping the palate it installs itself somewhere in the back of the head, allowing you to enjoy a nice balanced beer... and maybe another one...
Cask @GBBF 09. Strong smell of peaty whisky butt. Taste the same, with a decent enough dark ale just peeking out from below. Oddly weak tasting for 8.7 %.
Hoppy taste, little malt. Nice enough but somehow lacking in interest. 2345
Bottle @GBBF 09. Tastes of papaya sweeties. 78901234567890123456789012345
Flat, slightly sour honey taste. NondeScript smell, nice bright yellow colour.
Bottle @GBBF 09. Hazy pour, smells strongly of lychees. Much lighter tasting than its ABV would suggest. Bitter aftertaste.
Chocolate and fine cigars, washed down with eyebrow-raising quantities of schnapps and cherry brandy, its an entire christmas holiday condensed into beer. I dont care that it is August.
Cask @GBBF 09. Flat, but not limp; excellent sour taste and mouthfeel. Drawback: smells of piss.
Cask @GBBF 09; nice smell, good sourness, biscuity finish. however looks awful and seemed flat and lifeless
Regular at the Mag & Pie, Brentford. Hoppy taste without bitterness, like a lighter Sussex Best. Couldnt ask for a better springtime session ale.
Regular at the Mag & Pie, Brenttford. Very drinkable session ale, balanced, bit sweeter and fruitier than Sambrooks.

Big bottle from GBBF. Now this is a beer. Its basically Rodenbach "Vin De Cereale" only, you can find it. Slightly hazy pour but an absolutely cracking Flemish-sour taste with rich-tea biscuits and conflakes for afters.
The label doesnt look promising, but the beer is refreshing, malty, and not too bitter, with a smooth biscuity after-taste. Very quaffable indeed.
beer_name: Wissey Valley Capn Grumpys Best Bitter

review_blob: On draught at the monkey place in Herne Hill. Id never really got the idea of koelsch as a style before, but this one has a very nice malty flavour to it, definitely different from a pilsner. Maybe I should take that holiday in Duesseldorf after all.
beer_name: Meantime Kolner / Sainsburys Cologne Style Lager

review_blob: A very interesting bottle from GBBF. Good strong lambic flavour with a musky edge. Really nice soft palate.
Slightly cloudy with a decent head, smells a bit fruity. Noticeable alcohol to taste, hops and a slight acidic zing. Floral finish. Better than their "Weasel" but still decidedly amateur
UPDATED: AUG 16, 2008
Domestic bottle. Tastes of Thai lager but with a wicked chemical tang, almost metallic. Noticeably worse than the Singha available in Europe.
Offputtingly alcoholic (until you try Red Horse). Tastes of cheap lager. Thats all.

I drank this beer in Thailand because 1) it has a relatively sensible ABV and 2) you can get it for 25 baht a bottle, which normally makes it the cheapest one. It doesnt taste of anything much, which is pretty good for Thai lager.

Chestnut colour, slightly cloudy. Decent but short-lived creamy head; slightly fizzy, but not offputting. Served cold, ok this is Bangkok but the place is air-conditioned.... Light, nondeScript aroma, balanced initial taste soon becomes rather bitter. Like the Londoner itself, its perfect for ex-pats: itll remind you how average beer can be, so you dont get homesick.

Bottle, all over Laos. Beerlao is the best mass-produced beer in South-East Asia, which is to say, its a half decent beer in a region where the heat leads people to favour fizz over flavour. Pours slightly cloudy with a fluffy head. Nice clean wheatbeer-honey flavour when very cold; warmed up, its less enticing.

Chestnut brown with medium head; slightly soapy aroma. On the fizzy side, no heaviness (a plus given the climate) Honey-wheaty taste fruits up later but soon finishes. A refreshing beer, better cool than cold.

Advertised as "dark pilsner". Nice dark chestnut colour with a full creamy head. Sweetish bread-like smell is rather faint. At first taste a drinkable, down-to-earth pilsner with medium body and soft carbonation; long malty aftertaste with a little bitter coffee at the finish. A creditable brew.
Cask, GBBF 2006. Certailny less watery than cold coffee, also apparently contains alcohol. Brilliant if you dont like beer and the pub hasnt got a coffee machine.
Looks like pilsner, but falls short in most other respects. Smell not pleasant enough to analyze. Tastes of root beer. Still, I got through four bottles of the stuff so it cant be without merit.

Not much to add to existing comments. Looks lovely, smells OK, but if youre expecting a Belgian beer youll be unprepared for Rodenbachs sourness. On the other hand, if youve just drunk a decent cider, the malty beerness sings through. A difficult balancing act pulled off with style.
Bottle from Highbury Vintners, N5. Dark with little head. Malty, slightly treacly, taste - but not at all thick or heavy. Very drinkable.

Enticing smell and appearance, very dark with a fudge-brown, frothy head. Flavour a bit variable, normally thick and malty, but occasionally a rogue bottle disappoints. Not too heavy mouth-feel. Sam Smiths best stout, and a regular in my pub ordering roster

(2002 vintage) The ideal beer for a toasty Yuletide. Smells fruity enough but positively explodes with plum pudding and sherry greatness in the mouth. Little head, just a few bubbles, sumptuous colour. Gentle fizz gives it a pleasant tang, then a smouldering warmth takes over -- and stays. I shared a bottle with my significant other. This is my other bottle. I think you know what Im saying.

New style bottle, copious but short-lasting pink head. Full and sweet cherry-marzipan flavour gives way to some dryness at the very end. Lambic flavour could have been stronger but overall a worthy stab at a style rarely attempted in Britain.
